l arts, writers, radicals, wives, mothers, bar hostesses, department store and blue-collar workers. This unique collection of essays gives a broad, interdisciplinary view of contemporary Japanese women while challenging readers to see the development of Japanese women's lives against the backdrop of domestic and global change.These essays provide a "second generation" analysis of roles, issues and social change. The collection brings up to date the work begun in Gail Lee Bernstein's Recreating Japanese Women, 1600-1945 (California, 1991), exploring disparities between the current range of images of Japanese women and the reality behind the choices women make.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAllison, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAwaya, Nobuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Gail Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreighton, Millie R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHastings, Sally Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImamura, Anne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImamura, Anne E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLock, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarra, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMock, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrpett Long, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPainter, Andrew A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo